Prerequisite

This lab uses, as always, tidyverse package along with broom and caret we used for the last lab. And there are some new packages to install, whichare openintro for the email dataset, and caTools for the colAUC() function. To install the new packages, use install.packages().

library(tidyverse)
library(openintro)
library(caret)

Getting used to train()

train() is very powerful as it gives us a consistent framework for data analytics. We can use most of the statisticsl techniques available out there just a matter of replacing a few arguments in the function. Its definately worth your time getting used to as you might not need anything else when it comes to predictive modeling.

Lets use recap the previous lecture where we build a logistic model using glm().

glm(spam ~ num_char,
  data = email,
  family = "binomial"
)
## 
## Call:  glm(formula = spam ~ num_char, family = "binomial", data = email)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)     num_char  
##    -1.79874     -0.06207  
## 
## Degrees of Freedom: 3920 Total (i.e. Null);  3919 Residual
## Null Deviance:       2437 
## Residual Deviance: 2346  AIC: 2350

Using train() to build a logistic model is as simple as switching method.

spam_caret <- train(
  spam ~ num_char,
  data = email,
  method = "glm"
)
spam_caret$finalModel
## 
## Call:  NULL
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)     num_char  
##    -1.79874     -0.06207  
## 
## Degrees of Freedom: 3920 Total (i.e. Null);  3919 Residual
## Null Deviance:       2437 
## Residual Deviance: 2346  AIC: 2350

The two models show exactly the same output. Plus, train() does way more than what glm() is capable of!

Lets do the 10-fold cross validation using train(). Note that the arguments for cross validation go inside the trainControl().

spam_caret_cv10 <- train(
  spam ~ .,
  data = email,
  method = "glm",
  trControl = trainControl(
    method = "cv",
    number = 10
  )
)
spam_caret_cv10
## Generalized Linear Model 
## 
## 3921 samples
##   20 predictor
##    2 classes: 'NS', 'S' 
## 
## No pre-processing
## Resampling: Cross-Validated (10 fold) 
## Summary of sample sizes: 3528, 3530, 3530, 3528, 3528, 3528, ... 
## Resampling results:
## 
##   Accuracy   Kappa    
##   0.9138051  0.2463364

To get AUC instead of accuracy, we need two additional lines inside trainControl(): summaryFunction and classProbs. This is to tell that were dealing with a binary outcome, and want to use the secondary summary statstics (e.g., AUC, confusion matrix) from the probabilities calculated from glm

spam_caret_cv10_auc <- train(
  spam ~ .,
  data = email,
  method = "glm",
  trControl = trainControl(
    method = "cv",
    number = 10,
    summaryFunction = twoClassSummary, #<<
    classProbs = TRUE #<<
  )
)
spam_caret_cv10_auc
## Generalized Linear Model 
## 
## 3921 samples
##   20 predictor
##    2 classes: 'NS', 'S' 
## 
## No pre-processing
## Resampling: Cross-Validated (10 fold) 
## Summary of sample sizes: 3528, 3529, 3530, 3529, 3530, 3528, ... 
## Resampling results:
## 
##   ROC        Sens       Spec     
##   0.8838463  0.9895893  0.1767267

Decision tree

Decision tree tends to be more accurate than logistic regression because it is highly flexible, although it often comes as a weakness due to complexity. To build a tree, we need to use rpart method as modeling technique. Switch method from glm to rpart, and train() will take care of the rest.

mod_tree <- train(
    spam ~ .,
    data = email,
    method = "rpart", # <<
    trControl = trainControl(
        method = "cv",
        number = 10
    )
)
mod_tree
## CART 
## 
## 3921 samples
##   20 predictor
##    2 classes: 'NS', 'S' 
## 
## No pre-processing
## Resampling: Cross-Validated (10 fold) 
## Summary of sample sizes: 3530, 3529, 3529, 3528, 3528, 3529, ... 
## Resampling results across tuning parameters:
## 
##   cp          Accuracy   Kappa    
##   0.01089918  0.9313936  0.5052011
##   0.01471390  0.9237477  0.4163564
##   0.03405995  0.9127757  0.1450311
## 
## Accuracy was used to select the optimal model using the largest value.
## The final value used for the model was cp = 0.01089918.

train() by default grows three trees, and each of them has a different cp value. The results sugget the tree with the cp of 0.0108 has the highest accuracy of all three. Now, lets compare the accuracy between the logistic and tree model.

spam_caret_cv10$results$Accuracy
## [1] 0.9138051
max(mod_tree$results$Accuracy)
## [1] 0.9313936

Our tree model does slightly better than the logistic model, but not by far.

You can grow more trees by setting tuneLength to any number you want. Below is to grow 10 trees.

set.seed(123)
mod_trees <- train(
    spam ~ .,
    data = email,
    method = "rpart", # <<
    trControl = trainControl(
        method = "cv",
        number = 10
    ),
    tuneLength = 10
)
plot(mod_trees)

mod_trees$bestTune
##            cp
## 3 0.003633061

We have 10 different trees, and one with the cp of 0.00363 is our best tree with the highest accuracy of 93.5%. You can use plot and text to plot out the tree for detail.

plot(mod_trees$finalModel, uniform = TRUE)
text(mod_trees$finalModel, cex = .8)
